Kajol and Twinkle are serving up a talk show with a twist - equal parts masti, magic and maybe even some manic energy. Expect wild hot takes, controversial opinions and the kind of honesty that makes you say, â€œDude, same!â€ 
Joining them are their friends who just happen to be some of the biggest stars in the country (and even the world). With eight unique pairs gracing the couch this season, the conversations jump from filmy nostalgia to family drama, love, paparazzi, fame and everything in between.
What sets it apart is the unapologetic female gaze - a perspective thatâ€™s funny, sharp, and not afraid to hold up a mirror to society. One moment youâ€™re laughing embarrassingly loudly, the next youâ€™re caught off guard by an insight that might make you question your own life choices. 
Basically, itâ€™s a vibe: two women side-by-side, yapping with their friends. Think of it as the fun table at the party, sunny, chatty, and just unhinged enough to keep you hooked.

If you are curious about the future of entrepreneurship in regional content, this one is a must watch.

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Ruchir Sharma, bestselling author of 5 books, Chairman of Rockefeller International, and one of the worldâ€™s most respected investors and thinkers. He began writing for The Economic Times at just 17 and has since built a reputation for his sharp insights on politics, economics, and leadership. In this conversation, he opens up about his journey, his writing career, and the lessons from meeting global leaders including the time he met Vladimir Putin and was later asked to leave Russia.

We discuss the future of Indian politics, who could be the next Prime Minister, whether the opposition has a real chance, and how power is often misused in politics. Ruchir also shares his thoughts on world leaders like Putin and Trump, what emerging nations can learn from developed economies, and why the freebies culture may be holding India back. 

In the last segment, we dive into Indiaâ€™s growth story, from competition between states and infrastructure spending to unemployment, opportunities for young talent, and lessons we can take from China. Ruchir also explains what needs to change for India to rise as a true global power.

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Gaurav Gill, consultant psychologist and body language expert with Manobal Foundation, Delhi. With his expertise in reading human behaviour, he explains how much our gestures, expressions, and even the smallest body cues reveal about us. From spotting hidden emotions to decoding lies, his work bridges psychology and crime investigation in fascinating ways.

We discuss how professional criminals try to use specific gestures to appear innocent, how microexpressions can expose when someone is hiding the truth, and whether body language can help identify dangerous people, including pedophiles. Gaurav also breaks down the everyday mistakes we make, things as small as avoiding eye contact, crossing arms at the wrong moment, or mismatching words and actions that instantly create dislike and distrust in others. 

In the last segment, he shares the step-by-step process of detecting lies in high-stakes situations, the most difficult cases heâ€™s had to decode, and what serial killers actually feel after their first crime. Gaurav explains the psychology of deception, the science behind spotting danger, and the subtle signals most people miss.

title: Pehla Pyaar, Pehla Heartbreak ğŸ’” | Akshay Kumar, Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Alia Bhatt, Ranbir Kapoor
description:
First love feels like discovering fire for the very first time. Everything burns brighter, every touch leaves an echo, every word feels sacred. You go to school just to see them smile in the hallway, and suddenly that smile is the most important sight in the world. You stay awake until sunrise because their voice feels better than sleep itself. Every song makes sense, every poem speaks your truth, every star in the sky seems less beautiful than they are. Youâ€™d choose them in this universe and in every universe that could ever exist. In their presence, time bends, pain disappears, and forever feels like something you can finally hold in your hands. You think this is it, the kind of love poets spent lifetimes chasing, the kind of love that could never be broken.
But then life happens. Distance grows where closeness once lived. Silence floods the places where laughter once echoed. The person who was once your entire world becomes a stranger you still dream about at night. The same memories that once made you smile now burn like open wounds that refuse to heal. You replay conversations in your head, wonder what you could have said, what you could have done differently. Maybe it wasnâ€™t meant to be. Maybe the timing was cruel. Maybe the world was too heavy on two young hearts. And so, youâ€™re left staring at your phone, almost typing their name, before remembering that they are no longer yours to reach.
The hardest part isnâ€™t losing them. Itâ€™s learning how to exist without them. Waking up every day and remembering all over again that they are gone. Carrying a love that has nowhere to rest, like water slipping endlessly through your hands. Yet somehow, you keep breathing, you keep walking, you keep living with a heart that is shattered but still beating, broken but still full of hope. Because even after the fire fades, something inside you still aches to believe that beauty will return.
Sometimes, the love we cannot live without is the very love we must learn to survive without. â¤â€?

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Dr. Ashok Kumar Mittal, Member of Rajya Sabha and Founder & Chancellor of Lovely Professional University. From building one of Indiaâ€™s biggest private universities to stepping into politics, he shares how business and governance connect, what power really means, and the realities of navigating both worlds.

We discuss whether politicians are more powerful than businessmen, and how decisions are made in parliament, and why he chose politics as a way to drive change in education. Dr. Mittal also opens up about the business of education, the investments, challenges, and the criticism around universities focusing more on facilities than academics. He reflects on curriculum building, outdated policies, and the real reasons behind rising unemployment among graduates.

In the last segment, the conversation explores topics like the drug problem in Punjab, Bollywoodâ€™s influence, and whether even the most honest businessmen can be targeted by power. Dr. Mittal also shares personal stories about his familyâ€™s sweet shop, how he entered the automobile business, and the journey of starting LPU.

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Ajinkya Kulkarni, Co-founder & CEO of Wint Wealth, a platform making debt investments accessible for Indians. With years of experience in finance, Ajinkya shares practical insights on how to start investing, what mistakes to avoid, and how ordinary people can build wealth over time.

We explore questions most people have about money: how much you need before investing, whether to focus on active or passive income, and the differences between FDs, bonds, stocks, gold, and real estate. Ajinkya explains how banks pay interest, why sure-shot returns are a red flag, and what role emergency funds and insurance play. He also discusses India versus the US as investment destinations, financial advisory access for salaried individuals, and how to identify scams in the market.

In the last segment, he breaks down strategies for first-time investors, including where to put money across high, medium, and low-risk options, and shares advice for young professionals who want to double their income by upskilling. The conversation also explores whether a person from a low-income background in India can truly achieve financial independence, and how much wealth is required to achieve it.

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Gitanjali Babbar, the founder and director of Kat-Katha Foundation, an organisation dedicated to supporting women living and working in Delhiâ€™s red-light areas. Gitanjali has spent years working on the ground, listening to the unheard voices of sex workers, and building initiatives to create real change in their lives. She reveals eye-opening truths we donâ€™t see, but need to understand.

We discuss her experiences with the women trapped inside the red light areas, the brutal realities that women face, and the broken systems that trap them. From stories of violence and coercion to the myths society believes about consent and choice, Gitanjali explains how deeply rooted the problem is. 

In the last segment, she shares some of the most disturbing stories she has witnessed, the fear that keeps women from escaping, and how the cycle of exploitation continues generation after generation. She also opens up about what it will really take to bring change and the lessons her work at Kat-Katha has taught her.

In todayâ€™s episode, we have Suresh Sethi, Managing Director & CEO of Protean eGov Technologies Limited. With decades of experience in digital infrastructure and governance, he has played a key role in building systems like DigiLocker, Aadhaar services, and DigiYatra. In this conversation, he talks about how India is creating inclusive digital solutions that reach millions, and what makes our approach different from countries like the US and China.

We discuss the transformation of India Post, the role of digital identity, and how data privacy is being shaped by the new DPDP Act. Sethi explains how DigiLocker actually works, whether Aadhaar data is safe, and the systems that prevent fraud. The conversation also touches on digital elections, global comparisons, and how countries like Africa mirror Indiaâ€™s journey in adopting technology.

In the last segment, he talks about spotting entrepreneurial opportunities in developing economies, why local connection matters for any organisation, and which sectors still hold massive potential for digital disruption. Itâ€™s an inside look at how India is building trust, scale, and innovation for the future.

title: Alice In Borderland Season 3 | Official Trailer | Netflix
description:
The survival action series "Alice in Borderland" became the most watched Japanese Netflix title by worldwide audiences.

Now, the "games" that took the world by storm begin once again.

In the previous season, Arisu (#KentoYamazaki) and Usagi (#TaoTsuchiya) cleared all of the games and returned to the real world. They have since gotten married and established a happy life together. Their memories of the borderland were erased, but they see glimpses of it in dreams and hallucinations. One day, Usagi, led by afterlife researcher Ryuji (#KentoKaku), suddenly vanishes. At the same time as Usagi's disappearance, Banda (#HayatoIsomura) hands Arisu the final card: the Joker.

The uncharted journey led by the mysterious Joker card is about to unfold...

Season 3 of the Netflix Series "Alice in Borderland" is set for worldwide release on Thursday, 25 September, 2025, only on Netflix.

In this conversation, she opens up about the bond between humans and dogs and everything that goes into truly understanding them.

We talk about the history of manâ€™s relationship with dogs, the most intelligent and misunderstood breeds, and how to choose the right pet based on your lifestyle. In todayâ€™s episode, we have Karan Aujla, singer, lyricist, and one of the most influential voices in Punjabi music. He opens up about the struggles behind fame, from losing his parents at a young age to facing extortion threats and violence in Canada. Despite success, he reflects on the void he still feels and the fears that continue to shape his life and music.

We dive into his emotional side, how he views love, marriage, and family, why he writes songs from a female perspective, and the stories behind some of his most popular tracks. Karan also talks about his insecurities, the pressure of constantly creating, and the balance between vulnerability and strength as a public figure. He also reveals his habit of reckless spending, the making of his new album, and the artists he draws inspiration from.

In the last segment, he shares how loneliness follows him despite success, how his wife anchors him, and why he still feels a constant need to protect his loved ones. He also opens up about what truly defines happiness for him today. This episode was delivered by Porter.
